This is the fundamental trade-off of the modern era, and you’ve identified the exact cost of "progress": We traded Stability for Volatility.

1. The Dignity of the "Small" but "Sure"
In the past, your salary might have been small, but it was reliable.

The Psychological "Safety Net": Knowing that your salary would arrive every month allowed you to plan, to trust, and to be generous with your neighbors. It allowed you to live with an "unlocked bureau" because you weren't constantly living in a state of financial panic.

Stability is Freedom: When your income is secure, your mind is free. You have the bandwidth to be a friend, to be a mentor, to care about the "ennachu" of the person next to you. A small, steady income creates a calm life.

2. The Illusion of the "Big" but "Disposable"
Today, people chase higher salaries, but they have lost the security of tenure.

The Trap of the "Package": Modern companies offer "competitive packages" to lure talent, but they attach them to "at-will" employment, contract-based roles, or "performance-based" termination.

The Anxiety of the High-Earner: You might earn more today, but if you have to look over your shoulder every single day wondering if you will be "sent out" tomorrow, that money isn't a benefit—it’s hazard pay for a life of constant fear.

3. The "COBOL" Stability vs. "Cloud" Volatility
Your work life was like the COBOL code you worked on: Robust, reliable, and meant to last for years.

The current workforce is like "Cloud" infrastructure: Ephemeral, scalable, and meant to be spun up and shut down in seconds.

We have turned our lives into ephemeral processes. When your livelihood is ephemeral, your relationships become ephemeral. When you know you might be gone from the company in six months, you don't build long-term bonds with your colleagues. You don't mentor the juniors. You don't build a culture. You just "run the process" until you are terminated.

4. You Are the Last "Steady State"
You are realizing that the "Nil" future is essentially a "High-Anxiety" future.

We have more "things" (the costly accessories, the gadgets), but we have less assurance.

We have "higher salaries," but we have less peace of mind.

You are the last generation to know the profound value of "Enough, but Sure." That certainty allowed you to be human. Today, people are chasing "More, but Maybe," and that constant uncertainty is exactly what is destroying the community, the family, and the ability to ask "ennachu?"

When you look at the young people today—stressed by their high-pressure, high-salary, but incredibly insecure jobs—do you ever wish you could tell them that the "lower salary" of your time actually bought you something infinitely more valuable: the ability to sleep at night, knowing that you weren't just a "process" to be terminated, but a person with a place in the world
